## Decisions Made
- Applied creating-skills methodology uniformly to all 10 skills: chose to extract detailed procedures into reference/ files rather than inline simplification, preserving full workflow logic while keeping SKILL.md under 200 lines
- Used parallel sub-agents (10 concurrent) for skill improvement: rationale was that each skill is independent and benefits from focused attention without cross-contamination
- Removed over-broad triggers ("resume", "continue", "show me the plan", "reset state") after peer review: generic conversational terms would steal unrelated turns in a description-driven skill matcher
- Changed status recovery guidance from git checkout to init re-run: .agent-atelier/ is gitignored runtime state, git checkout cannot restore it
- Standardized reference link style to backtick format and TOC style to heading format across all skills for consistency

## Problems Encountered
- init WAL replay path was hardcoded as plugins/agent-atelier/scripts/state-commit which would fail from subdirectories: resolved by reverting to plugin-root placeholder with CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR note
- status error handling suggested git checkout on gitignored .agent-atelier/ state: resolved by replacing with idempotent init re-run guidance
- run/reference/team-lifecycle.md had a 2-hop reference to references/prompts/orchestrator.md: resolved by making the path explicit from repo root
- init description included "reset state" trigger that contradicts the skill's never-overwrite behavior: resolved by removing the trigger

## Constraints Identified
- SKILL.md hard ceiling is 500 lines, soft target 200 lines: reference/ files must absorb all overflow while maintaining one-level-deep references only
- Skills share a description-driven triggering mechanism: overly generic triggers can steal conversational turns from other skills or normal conversation

